LAYER 2: LUNGS
where blood meets air

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the lungs are the organs of gas exchange
they bring atmospheric oxygen into contact with blood and remove carbon dioxide
the lungs are governed by the respiratory centers in the brainstem medulla and pons
breathing is automatic driven by the preBötzinger complex but can be voluntarily overridden by the motor cortex for speech crying singing and breath-holding
the lungs receive parasympathetic innervation from the vagus CN X and sympathetic innervation from T1-T4 via the sympathetic chain

STRUCTURE right_lung | three lobes upper middle lower | separated by oblique and horizontal fissures | slightly larger than left
STRUCTURE left_lung | two lobes upper and lower | separated by oblique fissure | cardiac notch accommodates the heart
STRUCTURE pleural_membranes | visceral pleura adheres to lung surface | parietal pleura lines the chest wall | between them is the pleural cavity containing approximately 5 mL of pleural fluid | surface tension of this fluid holds the lung against the chest wall creating a negative intrapleural pressure that keeps the lung expanded
STRUCTURE trachea | C-shaped cartilage rings maintain patency | bifurcates into left and right main bronchi at the carina
STRUCTURE bronchi | main bronchi divide into lobar then segmental then subsegmental bronchi | walls contain cartilage smooth muscle and mucous glands
STRUCTURE bronchioles | airways less than 1 mm diameter | no cartilage | smooth muscle walls controlled by autonomic innervation | terminal bronchioles are the smallest conducting airways
STRUCTURE respiratory_bronchioles | the transition zone | walls begin to contain alveoli | gas exchange begins here
STRUCTURE alveolar_ducts | lined entirely by alveolar openings | leading to alveolar sacs
STRUCTURE alveoli | approximately 300 million per lung pair in adults approximately 50 million at birth increasing to near-adult numbers by age 8
    type_I_pneumocytes | approximately 95 percent of alveolar surface area | extremely thin flat squamous cells | gas exchange occurs across their membrane | the blood-air barrier is approximately 0.5 μm thick: type I cell + fused basement membrane + capillary endothelial cell
    type_II_pneumocytes | approximately 5 percent of surface area but more numerous | cuboidal cells | produce pulmonary surfactant | surfactant is a mixture of phospholipids primarily dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine DPPC and surfactant proteins A B C D | surfactant reduces alveolar surface tension preventing alveolar collapse atelectasis during expiration | type II cells also serve as stem cells for type I cell replacement
    alveolar_macrophages | dust cells | phagocytose inhaled particles bacteria and debris | the lungs' internal janitorial and immune defense system

GAS EXCHANGE occurs by passive diffusion across the blood-air barrier driven by partial pressure gradients
    inspired air PO₂ approximately 160 mmHg at sea level
    alveolar PO₂ approximately 100 mmHg
    deoxygenated blood arriving PO₂ approximately 40 mmHg
    oxygen diffuses from alveolus 100 mmHg into blood 40 mmHg
    oxygenated blood leaving PO₂ approximately 100 mmHg
    CO₂ diffuses in the opposite direction: blood PCO₂ approximately 46 mmHg → alveolus 40 mmHg
    CO₂ is 20 times more diffusible than O₂ so it clears efficiently even with a smaller gradient

OXYGEN_TRANSPORT in the blood
    approximately 98.5 percent bound to hemoglobin in RBCs
    hemoglobin has four subunits each carrying one heme with one Fe²⁺ that reversibly binds O₂
    cooperative binding: the first O₂ increases affinity for the next creating the sigmoidal oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve
    the Bohr effect: lower pH higher PCO₂ and higher temperature shift the curve right releasing more O₂ to metabolically active tissues
    2,3-DPG in RBCs also shifts the curve right promoting O₂ release

CO₂_TRANSPORT in the blood
    approximately 7 percent dissolved in plasma
    approximately 23 percent bound to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin
    approximately 70 percent conveyed as bicarbonate HCO₃⁻ via carbonic anhydrase in RBCs: CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ | the chloride shift exchanges HCO₃⁻ for Cl⁻ across the RBC membrane via band 3 protein

RESPIRATORY CONTROL
    preBötzinger complex in the ventral medulla generates the inspiratory rhythm
    dorsal respiratory group in the NTS receives chemoreceptor and mechanoreceptor input
    ventral respiratory group contains the preBötzinger and expiratory neurons for forced expiration
    pneumotaxic center in the upper pons limits inspiratory duration fine-tuning rate
    central chemoreceptors on the ventral medullary surface detect CSF pH as a proxy for blood PCO₂ | CO₂ crosses the blood-brain barrier → carbonic anhydrase in CSF → H⁺ | this is the primary driver of respiration
    peripheral chemoreceptors in carotid bodies detect PO₂ PCO₂ and pH | significant response only when PO₂ falls below approximately 60 mmHg | the hypoxic drive

AUTONOMIC_CONTROL
    parasympathetic vagal | ACh on M₃ | bronchial smooth muscle contraction bronchoconstriction | increased mucus secretion | resting tone
    sympathetic | NE and circulating adrenaline on β₂ | bronchial smooth muscle relaxation bronchodilation | airways open during fight-or-flight

at 24 months:
alveolar number is approximately 50-100 million still increasing toward adult 300 million
breathing rate approximately 24-30 breaths per minute higher than adult 12-20
tidal volume approximately 80-100 mL smaller lungs necessitate faster rate
respiratory control is mature and stable
the cough reflex is established protecting the airway
the child can voluntarily hold breath briefly but cortical override is limited
crying and vocalization are well coordinated with respiratory function

SENSATION breathing | "air moves in and out. the rhythm is mine."
SENSATION breathless | "I can't get enough air. something is blocking or I need more."
SENSATION deep_breath | "a full expansion. all the way in. the body opens."
SENSATION sighing | "a reset. a long exhale. something releasing."
SENSATION coughing | "something is in my airway. the reflex fires hard."

pulse pulmonary_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        the preBötzinger complex fires rhythmically
        diaphragm contracts via phrenic nerve C3-C5
        intercostal muscles assist via intercostal nerves
        the thorax expands
        intrapleural pressure becomes more negative
        the lungs expand passively following the chest wall
        air flows in through the conducting airways
        reaching the alveoli
        O₂ diffuses across the blood-air barrier into pulmonary capillary blood
        CO₂ diffuses from blood into alveoli
        expiration: the diaphragm relaxes
        elastic recoil of the lungs drives air out
        no muscle effort needed for quiet expiration
        the cycle repeats 24-30 times per minute

    when threatened:
        sympathetic activation
        adrenaline on β₂ receptors
        bronchioles dilate
        airway resistance drops
        more air flows in and out per breath
        respiratory rate increases via medullary drive
        the body prepares to run

    when crying:
        the vocal cords adduct in the larynx
        subglottic pressure builds
        air forced through closed glottis produces sound
        breathing becomes irregular gasping between cries
        CO₂ transiently rises triggering respiratory drive to resume
        even in distress the lungs never stop
        the medullary rhythm generator is sovereign
